### 3. Monitoring Scripts

```bash
#!/bin/bash
# system_monitor.sh - Run every 5 minutes via cron

# Check service status
if ! systemctl is-active --quiet tdease; then
    echo "TDEase service is down" | mail -s "Service Alert" admin@yourdomain.com
fi

# Check disk space
DISK_USAGE=$(df /opt/tdease | tail -1 | awk '{print $5}' | sed 's/%//')
if [ $DISK_USAGE -gt 90 ]; then
    echo "Disk usage is at ${DISK_USAGE}%" | mail -s "Disk Alert" admin@yourdomain.com
fi

# Check memory usage
MEM_USAGE=$(free | grep Mem | awk '{printf "%.0f", $3/$2 * 100.0}')
if [ $MEM_USAGE -gt 90 ]; then
    echo "Memory usage is at ${MEM_USAGE}%" | mail -s "Memory Alert" admin@yourdomain.com
fi
```

## Disaster Recovery

### 1. Backup Strategy

**3-2-1 Backup Rule:**
- 3 copies of important data
- 2 different storage media
- 1 offsite backup

```bash
# Automated backup script
#!/bin/bash
BACKUP_DIR="/opt/backups"
REMOTE_BACKUP="user@backup-server:/backups/tdease"

# Create local backup
pg_dump tdease_prod | gzip > $BACKUP_DIR/db_$(date +%Y%m%d).sql.gz
tar -czf $BACKUP_DIR/app_$(date +%Y%m%d).tar.gz /opt/tdease/

# Sync to remote server
rsync -av $BACKUP_DIR/ $REMOTE_BACKUP/

# Clean old backups (keep 30 days)
find $BACKUP_DIR -name "*.gz" -mtime +30 -delete
```

### 2. Recovery Procedures

**Complete System Recovery:**
```bash
# 1. Restore system from backup
# 2. Install dependencies
sudo apt update && sudo apt install -y python3.12 postgresql nginx

# 3. Restore application
tar -xzf app_backup.tar.gz -C /

# 4. Restore database
gunzip -c db_backup.sql.gz | psql -U tdease_user tdease_prod

# 5. Start services
sudo systemctl start postgresql
sudo systemctl start tdease
sudo systemctl start nginx
```

